    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/x2B8CTsRHo__qyLPbTzqx6wxQJg=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/69415192/vpavic_190102_3148_0136.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Photo by Vjeran Pavic / The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="B1ikxe"&gt;Dell is being sued in California over its claims that its &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/8/18167444/alienware-area-51m-desktop-laptop-features-price-release-date-ces-2019"&gt;Alienware Area-51m R1 laptop&lt;/a&gt; would offer “unprecedented upgradeability,” &lt;a href="https://www.tomshardware.com/news/dell-hit-with-fraud-case-over-alienware-area-51m-upgrade-claims"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Tom’s Hardware&lt;/em&gt; reports&lt;/a&gt;. Alienware customer Robert Felter is accusing the company of running a “false and misleading” marketing campaign, in which it promised that the laptop’s core components, including the CPU and GPU, could be swapped out for more powerful models. A year later, the &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2020/5/13/21256786/alienware-area-gaming-laptops-dell-spec-boost-intel-10th-gen-nvidia-gpu"&gt;Area-51m R1’s successor was announced&lt;/a&gt; with new components not available as upgrades for the original model.&lt;/p&gt;
